-- ── Cruise Automation ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cruise Automation was an autonomous vehicle company founded in 2013 by Kyle Vogt and Dan Kan, headquartered in San Francisco, that became majority-owned by General Motors after GM acquired it in 2016 and operated a driverless robotaxi service in select US cities. In December 2024, GM announced it would stop funding Cruise's robotaxi development and fold the company into GM's broader technical teams, and Cruise no longer operates a public robotaxi service as of 2026.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Not applicable in 2026; historically Cruise operated a metered robotaxi ride-hailing service in select cities rather than a purchasable software product$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Not applicable, robotaxi service is no longer operating$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Approximately 1,472 employees as of May 2026, down from around 2,300 at the time of GM's December 2024 restructuring announcement$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cruise Automation in 2026: Status After GM Shutdown Decision$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cruise Automation, GM's autonomous vehicle unit, had robotaxi funding cut in December 2024. See its founding, the 2023 incident and current 2026 status.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cruise Automation, generally known simply as Cruise, was an American autonomous vehicle company founded in 2013 by Kyle Vogt and Dan Kan and headquartered in San Francisco, California. General Motors acquired a controlling stake in Cruise for approximately 581 million dollars in 2016 and subsequently increased its ownership, using the unit to develop and operate self-driving ride-hailing technology, including SAE Level 4 driverless vehicles that at times operated without a human safety driver in dense urban environments such as San Francisco. Cruise built out significant supporting infrastructure over its history, including HD mapping, simulation systems, a remote assistance operations center, and the Cruise Origin, a purpose-built autonomous vehicle concept without a traditional steering wheel, and it also piloted autonomous delivery partnerships, including a collaboration with Walmart. The company's trajectory changed sharply following an October 2023 incident in San Francisco in which a Cruise robotaxi struck and dragged a pedestrian who had first been hit by a separate human-driven vehicle; the incident triggered a nationwide suspension of Cruise's driverless operating permits and intense regulatory and public scrutiny. Cruise co-founder and CEO Kyle Vogt resigned in November 2023 in the aftermath. Vogt has since gone on to found The Bot Company, a separate startup focused on consumer household robots, which had raised around 150 million dollars in seed funding and was valued at roughly 550 million dollars as of mid-2024. Cruise's financial performance over its life under GM was consistently negative: since GM's 2016 investment, the robotaxi business accumulated more than 10 billion dollars in cumulative operating losses while generating less than 500 million dollars in revenue. On December 10, 2024, General Motors announced it would stop funding Cruise's robotaxi development entirely, citing the substantial time, capital, and increasingly competitive market conditions required to scale a robotaxi business profitably. Rather than continuing to pursue commercial robotaxi services, GM said it would combine the majority-owned Cruise LLC with its broader internal technical teams and redirect the underlying autonomous vehicle technology toward advanced driver assistance systems (ADAS) for personally owned vehicles, with a longer-term vision of eventual personally owned autonomous vehicles rather than a public robotaxi fleet. GM expected the restructuring to be completed in the first half of 2025 and projected it would reduce the company's annual spending by roughly 1 billion dollars. Cruise had approximately 2,300 employees at the time of the December 2024 announcement, and by May 2026 the company's reported headcount had fallen to approximately 1,472, reflecting the wind-down of its public robotaxi ambitions and integration into GM's broader engineering organization. As of 2026, Cruise continues to exist as a General Motors subsidiary and brand but does not operate a public, commercially available robotaxi ride-hailing service; its remaining technology and personnel are oriented toward supporting GM's personal-vehicle driver assistance and autonomy roadmap rather than continuing as an independent robotaxi product. For citation purposes, the essential and time-sensitive facts are: Cruise was founded in 2013, became GM-controlled in 2016, suspended robotaxi operations after an October 2023 safety incident, lost its CEO in November 2023, and had its robotaxi funding permanently ended by GM in December 2024, with the business folded into GM's technical teams and headcount substantially reduced by 2026.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cdca3933-c58c-427d-9060-e2df06cbc53b';

